En este comentario se resume perfectamente lo que les va a pasar a los bancos dentro de poco m√°s de dos semanas. Los contratos de oro en papel dejan de tener valor y, en cambio, el oro f√≠sico tiene el 100% de su valor (nivel 1), con lo que, unido al cambio en el coeficiente de caja que expliqu√© el otro d√≠a, hace que los bancos tienen dos opciones: o se ponen a comprar oro como locos para equilibrar su balance o tendr√°n que quebrar.////
Previously, banks could hold gold on their balance sheets in the form of unallocated paper gold contracts without holding physical gold in tangible form. These paper contracts were considered as ‚Äúgood as gold‚Äù when it came to determining how much capital a bank needed to maintain on its balance sheet. Under the old rules, there was little incentive to hold physical gold, as it was only valued at 50% for reserve purposes. Basel III rules move physical gold from being considered a Tier-3 asset to being considered Tier-1, which allows physical gold in bullion form to be counted at 100% value for reserve purposes. Gold in unallocated paper contracts will no longer be considered an equal asset. For this reason, banks using paper forms of gold to help meet reserve requirements will have to convert those positions to physical metal, or risk becoming too undercapitalized to continue to function.
